Introduction

Have you ever wondered how stress, sleep, screen time, and lifestyle habits influence our memory and cognitive skills? In todays data-driven world, we can explore those questions through the power of data wrangling. This tutorial is designed for beginner R users who are comfortable with the basics of R but new to using the tidyverse to clean, manipulate, and visualize messy datasets

About the Dataset The dataset used in this tutorial is titled Human Cognitive Performance Analysis, and it is publicly available on Kaggle. It was published by user samxsam in 2023(It was updated on 04/02/2025) and includes simulated data from 80,000 individuals aged 1859.

The dataset records 13 variables, including:

  • Demographics: Age, Gender
  • Health habits: Sleep_Duration, Diet_Type, Caffeine_Intake, Exercise_Frequency
  • Behavioral factors: Stress_Level, Daily_Screen_Time
  • Cognitive metrics: Reaction_Time, Memory_Test_Score, Cognitive_Score, AI_Predicted_Score

This simulated dataset provides a realistic scenario for exploring how everyday habits may relate to cognitive performance. While it does not represent real medical data, it offers a valuable opportunity to practice data wrangling techniques with real-world context.

Dataset Source: Human Cognitive Performance Analysis

To begin, we load the dataset using read_csv() and take a first look at the structure using glimpse(). This helps us understand the number of rows, variables, and data types were working with.

Step 1: Cleaning the Data

Well start cleaning our dataset by renaming the columns to more consistent and readable names using rename(). Then, well use filter() to remove rows with missing values in key variables. This ensures our data is tidy and ready for analysis.

# Rename columns manually for consistency
cog_data <- cog_data %>%
  rename(
    user_id = User_ID,
    age = Age,
    gender = Gender,
    sleep = Sleep_Duration,
    stress = Stress_Level,
    diet_type = Diet_Type,
    screen_time = Daily_Screen_Time,
    exercise_frequency = Exercise_Frequency,
    caffeine_intake = Caffeine_Intake,
    reaction_time = Reaction_Time,
    memory = Memory_Test_Score,
    cognitive = Cognitive_Score,
    ai_predicted_score = AI_Predicted_Score
  )

# Remove rows with missing key values
cog_clean <- cog_data %>%
  filter(
    !is.na(memory),
    !is.na(cognitive),
    !is.na(gender),
    !is.na(stress)
  )

# Let's take a look  at cleaned data
glimpse(cog_clean)
## Rows: 80,000
## Columns: 13
## $ user_id            <chr> "U1", "U2", "U3", "U4", "U5", "U6", "U7", "U8", "U9
## $ age                <dbl> 57, 39, 26, 32, 50, 36, 48, 35, 29, 57, 54, 18, 51,
## $ gender             <chr> "Female", "Female", "Male", "Male", "Male", "Female

This summary tells us that our dataset includes 80,000 observations across 13 variables. It contains both numeric and categorical data, such as:

  • Age ranges from 18 to 59, with an average of about 38.5 years.
  • Sleep duration varies from 4 to 10 hours, averaging around 7.
  • Stress level ranges from 1 to 10, with a median of 5.
  • Cognitive and memory scores range from 0 to 100, with mean memory around 69.5 and cognitive around 58.2.

This overview helps us understand the scale and type of data were working with before moving on to wrangling and visualization.

Step 2: Creating New Variables and Summarizing

In this step, well use mutate() to create new variables that make our data easier to analyze. Specifically, well group stress levels into categories and create age groups. Then, well use group_by() and summarise() to explore average memory and cognitive scores across these categories.

# Creating a new variable for stress categories
cog_clean <- cog_clean %>%
  mutate(stress_cat = case_when(
    stress <= 3 ~ "Low",
    stress <= 7 ~ "Medium",
    TRUE ~ "High"
  ))

# Creating age group categories
cog_clean <- cog_clean %>%
  mutate(age_group = case_when(
    age < 25 ~ "1824",
    age < 35 ~ "2534",
    age < 45 ~ "3544",
    age < 55 ~ "4554",
    TRUE ~ "5559"
  ))

# Summarize average memory and cognitive score by stress category
stress_summary <- cog_clean %>%
  group_by(stress_cat) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_memory = mean(memory),
    avg_cognitive = mean(cognitive),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

stress_summary
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   stress_cat avg_memory avg_cognitive
##   <chr>           <dbl>         <dbl>
## 1 High             69.5          51.8
## 2 Low              69.4          64.6
## 3 Medium           69.6          58.1

This summary table shows the average memory and cognitive scores across different stress categories.

  • Individuals with low stress have the highest average cognitive score (~64.6), while those with high stress have the lowest (~51.8).
  • Interestingly, memory scores remain fairly consistent across all groups, hovering around 69.469.6.

These results suggest that while stress might not heavily impact memory, it appears to be linked to a noticeable drop in overall cognitive performance.

Step 3: Visualizing the Data

Now that weve wrangled and summarized our dataset, lets visualize some of the patterns to better understand how variables like stress and sleep relate to cognitive performance.

Well use ggplot2 to create two informative graphics: 1. A bar chart showing average memory scores across stress categories 2. A scatter plot showing the relationship between sleep duration and cognitive scores

First, well plot the average memory score for each stress category. This helps us visually compare how memory performance changes across different stress levels.

ggplot(stress_summary, aes(x = stress_cat, y = avg_memory, fill = stress_cat)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs( #Adding title and x, y 
    title = "Average Memory Score by Stress Category",
    x = "Stress Category",
    y = "Average Memory Score"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

This bar chart shows the average memory scores across different stress levels. Interestingly, the scores are very similar, regardless of stress category all hovering around 69.4 to 69.6. This suggests that stress may not have a strong effect on memory performance in this dataset. However, well need to look at other variables (like cognitive score) to see if stress influences different aspects of mental performance.

Next, lets try a scatter plot! Well use it to see if theres any relationship between how much people sleep and how well they perform on cognitive tests. Well use two variables: hours of sleep and cognitive score, and plot the correlation between them.

ggplot(cog_clean, aes(x = sleep, y = cognitive)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3, color = "steelblue") + #adding color 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "Cognitive Score vs. Sleep Duration",
    x = "Hours of Sleep",
    y = "Cognitive Score"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() #using theme minimal
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

This scatter plot shows the relationship between sleep duration and cognitive score. Each point represents an individuals cognitive score based on how many hours of sleep they got.

While the data points are spread out, the red trend line (generated with geom_smooth(method = "lm")) shows a slight positive correlation suggesting that people who sleep more tend to have slightly higher cognitive scores.

Conclusion

In this tutorial, we explored how to clean and wrangle a real-world dataset on human cognitive performance using the dplyr package in R. Through filtering, mutating, summarizing, and visualizing the data, we uncovered some interesting patterns.

Key takeaway:

Stress levels appeared to have little effect on memory, but higher stress was linked to lower cognitive scores.

Sleep duration showed a slight positive relationship with cognitive performance, suggesting that more sleep may support better mental function.

These results are valuable because they highlight how simple lifestyle factors like stress and sleep could influence cognitive abilities. This project demonstrates the power of data wrangling to turn messy information into clear insights. Whether youre preparing data for analysis or creating visualizations to share findings, tidy data and thoughtful exploration are key.
